# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: amorphea
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:amorphea/acinetactis] The validity and classification of this genus is contested.
[src:amorphea/acinetactis] In 1914, Adolf Pascher cast doubt on *Acinetactis*, suggesting that it was a junior synonym of *Dimorpha mutans*.
[src:amorphea/acinetactis] Cavalier-Smith classified *Acinetactis* as a heliomonad in 1993.
[src:amorphea/acinetactis] Bass et al. suggested in 2009 that the genus was a cercozoan in the class Granofilosea.
[src:amorphea/acritarch] Acritarchs were originally defined as non-acid soluble (i.e. non-carbonate, non-siliceous) organic-walled microfossils consisting of a central cavity, and whose biological affinities cannot be determined with certainty.
[src:amorphea/acritarch] Most commonly they are composed of thermally altered acid-insoluble carbon compounds (kerogen).
[src:amorphea/acritarch] Acritarchs may include the remains of a wide range of quite different kinds of organisms—ranging from the egg cases of small metazoans to resting cysts of many kinds of chlorophyta (green algae).
[src:amorphea/acritarch] It is likely that most acritarch species from the Paleozoic represent various stages of the life cycle of algae that were ancestral to the dinoflagellates.
[src:amorphea/acritarch] The nature of the organisms associated with Precambrian acritarchs is generally not well understood, though many are probably related to unicellular marine algae.
[src:amorphea/acritarch] In theory, when the biological source (taxon) of an acritarch does become known, that particular microfossil is removed from the acritarchs and classified with its proper group.
[src:amorphea/acritarch] While the classification of acritarchs into form genera is entirely artificial, it is not without merit, as the form taxa show traits similar to those of genuine taxa—for example an 'explosion' in the Cambrian and a mass extinction at the end of the Permian.
[src:amorphea/acritarch] The informal group Acritarcha Evitt 1963 was originally divided into these Subgroups: Acanthomorphitae, Polygonomorphitae, Prismatomorphitae, Oömorphitae, Netromorphitae, Dinetromorphitae, Stephanomorphitae, Pteromorphitae, Herkomorphitae, Platymorphitae, Sphaeromorphitae, and Disphaeromorphitae.
[src:amorphea/acritarch] In the end, it may well be, as Moczydłowska et al. suggested in 2011, that many acritarchs will, in fact, turn out to be algae.
[src:amorphea/acritarch] Acritarchs are found in sedimentary rocks from the present back into the Archean.
[src:amorphea/acritarch] They are typically isolated from siliciclastic sedimentary rocks using hydrofluoric acid but are occasionally extracted from carbonate-rich rocks.
[src:amorphea/acritarch] They are excellent candidates for index fossils used for dating rock formations in the Paleozoic Era and when other fossils are not available.
[src:amorphea/acritarch] Because most acritarchs are thought to be marine (pre-Triassic), they are also useful for palaeoenvironmental interpretation.
[src:amorphea/acritarch] The Archean and earliest Proterozoic microfossils termed "acritarchs" may actually be prokaryotes.
[src:amorphea/acritarch] The earliest eukaryotic acritarchs known (as of 2020) are from between 1950 and 2150 million years ago.
[src:amorphea/acritarch] At about 1 billion years ago the organisms responsible for acritarchs started to increase in abundance, diversity, size, complexity of shape, and especially, the size and number of spines.
[src:amorphea/acritarch] Their populations crashed during periods of extensive worldwide glaciations that covered the majority of the planet, but they proliferated in the Cambrian explosion and reached their highest diversity in the Paleozoic.
[src:amorphea/acritarch] The increased spininess 1000 million years ago possibly resulted from the need for defense against predators, especially predators large enough to swallow them or tear them apart.
[src:amorphea/acritarch] Other groups of small organisms from the Neoproterozoic era also show signs of anti-predator defenses.
[src:amorphea/acritarch] Further evidence that acritarchs were subject to herbivory around this time comes from a consideration of taxon longevity.
[src:amorphea/acritarch] Approximately 1,000 million years ago, species longevity fell sharply, suggesting that predation pressure, probably by protist herbivores, became an important factor.
[src:amorphea/acritarch] Predation would have kept populations in check, meaning that some nutrients were left unused, and new niches were available for new species to occupy.
[src:amorphea/acritarch] There are over 900 described genera; the following is a partial list, from Fossilid.info.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] The **actinophryids** are an order of heliozoa, a polyphyletic array of amoebae.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] They are common in fresh water and occasionally found in marine and soil habitats.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] Actinophryids are unicellular and roughly spherical in shape, with many axopodia that radiate outward from the cell body.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] Axopodia are a type of pseudopodia that are supported by hundreds of microtubules arranged in interlocking spirals and forming a needle-like internal structure or axoneme.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] Small granules, extrusomes, that lie under the membrane of the body and axopodia capture flagellates, ciliates and small metazoa that make contact with the arms.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] Actinophryids are largely aquatic protozoa with a spherical cell body and many needle-like axopodia.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] They resemble the shape of a sun due to this structure, which is the inspiration for their common name: heliozoa, or "sun-animalcules".
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] Their bodies, without arms, range in size from a few tens of micrometers to slightly under a millimeter across.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] The outer region of cell body is often vacuolated.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] The endoplasm of actinophryids is less vacuolated than the outer layer, and a sharp boundary layer may be seen by light microscopy.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] The organisms can be either mononucleate, with a single, well defined nucleus in the center of the cell body, or multinucleate, with 10 or more nuclei located under the outer vacuolated layer of cytoplasm.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] The cytoplasm of actinophryids is often granular, similar to that of *Amoeba*.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] Actinophryid cells may fuse when feeding, creating larger aggregated organisms.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] Fine granules that occur just under the cell membrane are used up when food vacuoles form to enclose prey.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] Actinophryids may also form cysts when food is not readily available.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] A layer of siliceous plates is deposited under the cell membrane during the encystment process.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] Contractile vacuoles are common in these organisms, which are presumed to use them to maintain body volume by expelling fluids to compensate for the entry of water by osmosis.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] Contractile vacuoles are visible as clear bulges from the surface of the cell body that slowly fill then rapidly deflate, expelling their contents into the environment.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] The most distinctive characteristic of the actinophryids is their axopodia.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] These axopodia consist of a central, rigid rod which is coated in a thin layer of ectoplasm.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] In *Actinophrys* the axonemes end on the surface of the central nucleus, and in the multicellular *Actinosphaerium* they end at or near nuclei.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] The axonemes are composed of microtubules arranged in a double spiral pattern characteristic of the order.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] Due to their long, parallel construction, these microtubules demonstrate strong birefringence.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] These axopodia are used for prey capture, in movement, cell fusion and perhaps division.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] They are stiff but may flex especially near their tips, and are highly dynamic, undergoing frequent construction and destruction.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] When used to collect prey items, two methods of capture have been noted, termed axopodial flow and rapid axopodial contraction.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] Axopodial flow involves the slow movement of a prey item along the surface of the axopod as the ectoplasm itself moves, while rapid axopodial contraction involves the collapse of the axoneme's microtubule structure.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] This behavior has been documented in many species, including *Actinosphaerium nucleofilum*, *Actinophrys sol*, and *Raphidiophrys contractilis*.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] The rapid axopodial contraction occurs at high speed, often in excess of 5mm/s or tens of body lengths per second.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] The axopodial contractions have been shown to be highly sensitive to environmental factors such as temperature and pressure as well as chemical signals like Ca2+ and colchicine.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] Reproduction in actinophryids generally takes place via fission, where one parent cell divides into two or more daughter cells.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] For multinucleate heliozoa, this process is plasmotomic as the nuclei are not duplicated prior to division.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] It has been observed that reproduction appears to be a response to food scarcity, with an increased number of divisions following the removal of food and larger organisms during times of food excess.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] Actinophryids also undergo autogamy during times of food scarcity.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] This is better described as genetic reorganization than reproduction, as the number of individuals produced is the same as the initial number.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] Nonetheless, it serves as a way to increase genetic diversity within an individual which may improve the likelihood of expressing favorable genetic traits.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] Plastogamy has also been extensively documented in actinophryids, especially in multinucleate ones.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] *Actinosphaerium* were observed to combine freely without the combination of nuclei, and this process sometimes resulted in more or less individuals than originally combined.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] This process is not caused merely by contact between two individuals but can be caused by damage to the cell body.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] Under unfavourable conditions, some species will form a cyst.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] This is often the product of autogamy, in which case the cysts produced are zygotes.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] Cells undergoing this process withdraw their axopodia, adhere to the substrate, and take on an opaque and grayish appearance.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] This cyst then divides until only uninucleate cells remain.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] The cyst wall is thickly layered 7–8 times and includes gelatinous layers, layers of silica plates, and iron.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] Originally placed in Heliozoa (Sarcodina), the actinophryids are now understood to be part of the stramenopiles.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] They are unrelated to centrohelid and desmothoracid heliozoa with which they had been previously classified.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] There are several genera included within this classification.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] *Actinophrys* are smaller and have a single, central nucleus.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] Most have a cell body 40–50 micrometer in diameter with axopods around 100 μm in length, though this varies significantly.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] *Actinosphaerium* are several times larger, from 200 to 1000 μm in diameter, with many nuclei and are found exclusively in fresh water.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] A third genus, *Camptonema*, has a debated status.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] It has been observed once and was treated as a junior subjective synonym of *Actinosphaerium* by Mikrjukov & Patterson in 2001, but as a valid genus by Cavalier-Smith & Scoble (2013).
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] *Heliorapha* is a further debated taxon, it being a new generic vehicle for the species *azurina* that was initially assigned to the genus *Ciliophrys*.
[src:amorphea/actinophryid] According to the latest review of actinophryid classifications, they are organized into two genera and six species.
[src:amorphea/algospongia] Algospongia (vernacular name: algosponges) is a taxon of calcified fossil organisms comprising around 90 accepted genera and several hundred species, treated taxonomically as a single class in an unspecified phylum.
[src:amorphea/algospongia] Originally considered to be fossil sponges or "pseudo algae", an assignment now refuted, their taxonomic position is somewhat unresolved.
[src:amorphea/algospongia] Of the three most prominent recent researchers, B.
[src:amorphea/algospongia] Mamet (Belgium) assigns certain families (e.g.
[src:amorphea/algospongia] Palaeoberesellaceae, Beresellaceae and Issinellaceae) to Chlorophyta (green algae) as an order of that phylum (Palaeosiphonocladales), at least one other family (Ungdarellaceae) to Rhodophyta (red algae), and some other genera (*Groenlandella*, *Labyrinthoconus*) simply to "Microproblematica".
[src:amorphea/algospongia] Cózar (Spain) treated Algospongia (such as the family Calcifoliaceae) as Algae *incertae sedis*, before deciding (in 2010) against any algal affinity and reassigning them to the [zoological] protists, as a group possibly paralleling the Foraminifera.
[src:amorphea/algospongia] Since that paper, Cózar has continued to use zoological terminology in his published works, while Vachard has once again assigned the group to the Algae *incertae sedis*, lying hypothetically mid-way between the extant Rhodophyta and Chlorophyta.
[src:amorphea/algospongia] A number of the genera allocated to Algospongia in the present treatment (which follows Vachard & Cózar, 2010 in the main) were recently (2021) treated as either Foraminifera, or as red or green algae, in the World Register of Marine Species, a situation that is currently under revision.
[src:amorphea/algospongia] Members of the group occur in the fossil record from the Ordovician to the Late Permian periods, although only *Wetheredella* is prominent prior to the start of the Devonian.
[src:amorphea/algospongia] Algosponges are described as a group of sessile or attached microorganisms with characteristic calcified walls described as "yellowish, apparently granular" that are frequently perforated, and possess either lateral or terminal apertures between successive chambers or cells.
[src:amorphea/algospongia] The treatment below is based on that published by Vachard & Cózar in 2010, (alternative, botanical treatment indicated separated by "/"); more recent genera (post 2010) and, in some cases, corrections have been added per other available sources.
[src:amorphea/algospongia] The possibly analogous Foraminifera (protists or Protozoa in many classifications) are members of the clade SAR, which is presently assigned to the kingdom Chromista in many classifications.
[src:amorphea/algospongia] The stratigraphic range of selected algosponge genera is summarised in Figure 15 of Vachard & Cózar (2010).
[src:amorphea/algospongia] From this Figure it is apparent that *Wetheredella* is the sole representative of the group from the Upper Ordovician through the Silurian, being joined by *Asphaltinoides* a little before the Silurian ends.
[src:amorphea/algospongia] The majority of other genera then develop within, and/or are restricted to, the Devonian through Carboniferous periods, with a relatively small number (16) persisting through the Permian before all becoming extinct by the end of that period.
[src:amorphea/algospongia] The same authors also comment (their "Conclusion" no.
[src:amorphea/algospongia] As mentioned above, members of the claimed single class Algospongia have been assigned to different taxonomic groups over time, with no clear consensus emerging.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] The **alveolates** are a group of protists, considered a major clade or superphylum within Eukaryota.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] They are currently grouped with the Stramenopiles and Rhizaria among the protists with tubulocristate mitochondria into the SAR supergroup.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] The most notable shared characteristic is the presence of cortical (near the surface) alveoli (sacs).
[src:amorphea/alveolate] These are flattened vesicles (sacs) arranged as a layer just under the membrane and supporting it, typically contributing to a flexible pellicle (thin skin).
[src:amorphea/alveolate] In armored dinoflagellates they may contain stiff plates.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] Alveolates have mitochondria with tubular cristae (invaginations), and cells often have pore-like intrusions through the cell surface.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] The group contains free-living and parasitic organisms, predatory flagellates, and photosynthetic organisms.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] Almost all sequenced mitochondrial genomes of ciliates and apicomplexa are linear.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] The mitochondria almost all carry mtDNA of their own but with greatly reduced genome sizes.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] Exceptions are *Cryptosporidium* which are left with only a mitosome, the circular mitochondrial genomes of *Acavomonas* and *Babesia microti*, and *Toxoplasma*'s highly fragmented mitochondrial genome, consisting of 21 sequence blocks which recombine to produce longer segments.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] The relationship of apicomplexa, dinoflagellates and ciliates had been suggested during the 1980s, and this was confirmed in the early 1990s by comparisons of ribosomal RNA sequences, most notably by Gajadhar *et al*.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] Cavalier-Smith introduced the formal name Alveolata in 1991, although at the time he considered the grouping to be a paraphyletic assemblage.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] Many biologists prefer the use of the colloquial name 'alveolate'.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] Alveolata include around six major groups.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] The Acavomonidia and Colponemidia were previously grouped together as colponemids, a taxon now split because each has a distinctive organization or ultrastructural identity.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] The Acavomonidia are closer to the dinoflagellate/perkinsid group than the Colponemidia are.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] As such, the informal term "colponemids", as it stands currently, covers two non-sister groups within Alveolata: the Acavomonidia and the Colponemidia.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] As of present, five genera of colponemids are recognized.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] The Apicomplexa and dinoflagellates may be more closely related to each other than to the ciliates.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] Both have plastids, and most share a bundle or cone of microtubules at the top of the cell.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] In apicomplexans this forms part of a complex used to enter host cells, while in some colorless dinoflagellates it forms a peduncle used to ingest prey.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] Various other genera are closely related to these two groups, mostly flagellates with a similar apical structure.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] These include free-living members in *Oxyrrhis* and *Colponema*, and parasites in *Perkinsus*, *Parvilucifera*, *Rastrimonas* and the ellobiopsids.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] In 2001, direct amplification of the rRNA gene in marine picoplankton samples revealed the presence of two novel alveolate lineages, called group I and II.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] Group I has no cultivated relatives, while group II is related to the dinoflagellate parasite *Amoebophrya*, which was classified until now in the Syndiniales dinoflagellate order.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] Some studies suggested the haplosporids, mostly parasites of marine invertebrates, might belong here, but they lack alveoli and are now placed among the Cercozoa.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] The ellobiopsids are of uncertain relation within the alveolates.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] Silberman et al 2004 establish that the *Thalassomyces* genus of ellobiopsids are alveolates using phylogenetic analysis, however as of 2016 no more certainty exists on their place.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] The development of plastids among the alveolates is intriguing.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] Cavalier-Smith proposed the alveolates developed from a chloroplast-containing ancestor, which also gave rise to the Chromista (the chromalveolate hypothesis).
[src:amorphea/alveolate] Other researchers have speculated that the alveolates originally lacked plastids and possibly the dinoflagellates and Apicomplexa acquired them separately.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] However, it now appears that the alveolates, the dinoflagellates, the Colpodellida and the heterokont algae acquired their plastids from a red alga with evidence of a common origin of this organelle in all these four clades.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] A Bayesian estimate places the evolution of the alveolate group at ~850 million years ago.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] The Alveolata consist of Myzozoa, ciliates, and colponemids.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] In other words, the term Myzozoa, meaning "to siphon the contents from prey", may be applied informally to the common ancestor of the subset of alveolates that are neither ciliates nor colponemids.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] Predation upon algae is an important driver in alveolate evolution, as it can provide sources for endosymbiosis of novel plastids.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] The term Myzozoa is therefore a handy concept for tracking the history of the alveolate group.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] The ancestors of the alveolate group may have been photosynthetic.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] The ancestral alveolate probably possessed a plastid.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] Chromerids, apicomplexans, and peridinin dinoflagellates have retained this organelle.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] In one school of thought the common ancestor of the dinoflagellates, apicomplexans, *Colpodella*, Colpodellida, and *Voromonas* was a myzocytotic predator with two heterodynamic flagella, micropores, trichocysts, rhoptries, micronemes, a polar ring and a coiled open sided conoid.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] While the common ancestor of alveolates may also have possessed some of these characteristics, it has been argued that Myzocytosis was not one of these characteristics, as ciliates ingest prey by a different mechanism.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] An ongoing debate concerns the number of membranes surrounding the plastid across apicomplexans and certain dinoflagellates, and the origin of these membranes.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] This ultrastructural character can be used to group organisms and if the character is in common, it can imply that phyla had a common photosynthetic ancestor.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] Ciliates are a model alveolate, having been genetically studied in great depth over the longest period of any alveolate lineage.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] They are unusual among eukaryotes in that reproduction involves a micronucleus and a macronucleus.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] Their reproduction is easily studied in the lab, and made them a model eukaryote historically.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] Being entirely predatory and lacking any remnant plastid, their development as a phylum illustrates how predation and autotrophy are in dynamic balance and that the balance can swing one way or other at the point of origin of a new phylum from mixotrophic ancestors, causing one ability to be lost.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] Few algae have been studied for epigenetics.
[src:amorphea/alveolate] Those for which epigenetic data are available include some algal alveolates.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Ingestion of the mushroom can cause poisoning, especially in children and those seeking its hallucinogenic effects, due to psychoactive compounds like muscimol and ibotenic acid; however, fatal poisonings are extremely rare.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Parboiling reduces toxicity; drying converts ibotenic acid into muscimol while retaining psychoactive effects.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Some cultures use it as food after preparation.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Indigenous peoples of Siberia used *A. muscaria* as an inebriant and entheogen.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] It has been controversially linked to Santa Claus, Viking berserkers, Vedic soma, and early Christianity, though evidence is sparse and disputed.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Its rise in the 2020s as a hallucinogen has led to governmental scrutiny.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The name of the mushroom in many European languages is thought to derive from its use as an insecticide when sprinkled in milk.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] This practice has been recorded from Germanic- and Slavic-speaking parts of Europe, as well as the Vosges region and pockets elsewhere in France, and Romania.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Albertus Magnus was the first to record it in his work *De vegetabilibus* some time before 1256, commenting, "it is called the fly mushroom because it is powdered in milk to kill flies".
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The 16th-century Flemish botanist Carolus Clusius traced the practice of sprinkling it into milk to Frankfurt in Germany, while Carl Linnaeus, the "father of taxonomy", reported it from Småland in southern Sweden, where he had lived as a child.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] He described it in volume two of his *Species Plantarum* in 1753, giving it the name *Agaricus muscarius*, the specific epithet deriving from Latin *musca* meaning "fly".
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] It gained its current name in 1783, when placed in the genus *Amanita* by Jean-Baptiste Lamarck, a name sanctioned in 1821 by the "father of mycology", Swedish naturalist Elias Magnus Fries.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The starting date for all the mycota had been set by general agreement as January 1, 1821, the date of Fries's work, and so the full name was then *Amanita muscaria* (L.:Fr.) Hook.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The 1987 edition of the International Code of Botanical Nomenclature changed the rules on the starting date and primary work for names of fungi, and names can now be considered valid as far back as May 1, 1753, the date of publication of Linnaeus's work.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Hence, Linnaeus and Lamarck are now taken as the namers of *Amanita muscaria* (L.) Lam..
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The English mycologist John Ramsbottom reported that *Amanita muscaria* was used for getting rid of bugs in England and Sweden, and *bug agaric* was an old alternative name for the species.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] French mycologist Pierre Bulliard reported having tried without success to replicate its fly-killing properties in his work **Histoire des plantes vénéneuses et suspectes de la France** (1784), and proposed a new binomial name *Agaricus pseudo-aurantiacus* because of this.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] One compound isolated from the fungus is 1,3-diolein (1,3-di(cis-9-octadecenoyl)glycerol), which attracts insects.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] It has been hypothesised that the flies intentionally seek out the fly agaric for its intoxicating properties.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] An alternative derivation proposes that the term *fly-* refers not to insects as such but rather the delirium resulting from consumption of the fungus.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] This is based on the medieval belief that flies could enter a person's head and cause mental illness.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Several regional names appear to be linked with this connotation, meaning the "mad" or "fool's" version of the highly regarded edible mushroom *Amanita caesarea*.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Hence there is **oriol foll** "mad oriol" in Catalan, *mujolo folo* from Toulouse, **concourlo fouolo** from the Aveyron department in Southern France, **ovolo matto** from Trentino in Italy.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] A local dialect name in Fribourg in Switzerland is *tsapi de diablhou*, which translates as "Devil's hat".
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] A 2006 molecular phylogenetic study of different regional populations of *A. muscaria* by mycologist József Geml and colleagues found three distinct clades within the species, roughly representing Eurasian, Eurasian "subalpine", and North American populations.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Specimens belonging to all three clades have been found in Alaska; this has led to the hypothesis that this was the centre of diversification for this species.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The study also looked at four named varieties of the species: var.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] All four were found within both the Eurasian and North American clades, evidence that the forms are polymorphisms rather than distinct subspecies or varieties.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Thus *A. muscaria* as it stands currently is, evidently, a species complex.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Both of these last two are found with *Eucalyptus* and *Cistus* trees, and it is unclear whether they are native or introduced from Australia.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] A large, conspicuous mushroom, *A. muscaria* is generally common and numerous where it grows, and is often found in groups with basidiocarps in all stages of development.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Fly agaric fruiting bodies emerge from the soil looking like white eggs.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] After emerging from the ground, the cap has an irregular distribution small white to yellow pyramid-shaped warts.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] These are remnants of the universal veil, a membrane that encloses the entire mushroom when it is still very young.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Dissecting the mushroom at this stage reveals a characteristic yellowish layer of skin under the veil, which helps identification.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] As the fungus grows, the red colour appears through the broken veil and the warts become less prominent; they do not change in size, but are reduced relative to the expanding skin area.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The cap changes from globose to hemispherical and finally to plate-like in mature specimens.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The bright red cap ranges from 5–30 centimetres (2–12 inches) in diameter.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Age and rain may cause the red colour to fade and the warts to fall off.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The free gills are white, as is the spore print.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The oval spores measure 9–13 by 6.5–9 μm; they do not turn blue with the application of iodine.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The stipe is white, 5–20 cm (2–8 in) high by 1–2 cm (1⁄2–1 in) wide, and has the slightly brittle, fibrous texture typical of many large mushrooms.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] At the base is a bulb that bears universal veil remnants in the form of two to four distinct rings or ruffs.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Between the basal universal veil remnants and gills are remnants of the partial veil (which covers the gills during development) in the form of a white ring.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] It can be quite wide and flaccid with age.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] There is generally no associated smell other than a mild earthiness.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Although very distinctive in appearance, the fly agaric has been mistaken for other yellow to red mushroom species in the Americas, such as *Armillaria* cf.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] *mellea* and the edible *A. basii*—a Mexican species similar to *A. caesarea* of Europe.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Poison control centres in the U.S. and Canada have become aware that *amarill* (Spanish for 'yellow') is a common name for the *A. caesarea*-like species in Mexico.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] *A. caesarea* is distinguished by its entirely orange to red cap, which lacks the numerous white warty spots of the fly agaric (though these sometimes wash away during heavy rain).
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Furthermore, the stem, gills and ring of *A. caesarea* are bright yellow, not white.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The volva is a distinct white bag, not broken into scales.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] In Australia, the introduced fly agaric may be confused with the native *A. xanthocephala* (vermilion grisette), which grows in association with eucalypts.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The latter species generally lacks the white warts of *A. muscaria* and bears no ring.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Additionally, immature button forms resemble puffballs.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] *A. muscaria* is also morphologically similar to closely related species in *A. stirps Muscaria*, including *A. persicina*, and *A. chrysoblema*.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Ectomycorrhizal, *A. muscaria* forms symbiotic relationships with many trees, including pine, oak, spruce, fir, birch, and cedar.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Commonly seen under introduced trees, *A. muscaria* is the fungal equivalent of a weed in New Zealand, Tasmania and Victoria, forming new associations with southern beech (*Nothofagus*).
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The species is also invading a rainforest in Australia, where it may be displacing the native species.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] It appears to be spreading northwards, with recent reports placing it near Port Macquarie on the New South Wales north coast.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] It was recorded under silver birch (*Betula pendula*) in Manjimup, Western Australia in 2010.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Although it has apparently not spread to eucalypts in Australia, it has been recorded associating with them in Portugal.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Commonly found throughout the great Southern region of western Australia, it is regularly found growing on *Pinus radiata*.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Adults of the pleasing fungus beetle *Tritoma biguttata biguttata* have been recorded from this mushroom, but it does not seem to be a regular food source for them.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Deaths from *A. muscaria* have been reported in historical journal articles and newspaper reports, but with modern medical treatment, fatal poisoning from ingesting this mushroom is extremely rare.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Many books list *A. muscaria* as deadly, but according to David Arora, this is an error that implies the mushroom is far more toxic than it is.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Furthermore, the North American Mycological Association has stated that there were "no reliably documented cases of death from toxins in these mushrooms in the past 100 years".
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The active constituents of *A. muscaria* are water-soluble; boiling and then discarding the cooking water at least partly detoxifies it.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Drying may increase potency, as the process facilitates the conversion of ibotenic acid to the more potent muscimol.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] According to some sources, once detoxified, the mushroom becomes edible.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Patrick Harding describes the Sami custom of processing the fly agaric through reindeer.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Muscarine, discovered in 1869, was long thought to be the active hallucinogenic agent in *A. muscaria*.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Muscarine binds with muscarinic acetylcholine receptors leading to the excitation of neurons bearing these receptors.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The levels of muscarine in *A. muscaria* are minute when compared with other poisonous fungi such as *Inosperma erubescens*, the small white *Clitocybe* species *C. dealbata* and *C. rivulosa*.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The level of muscarine in *A. muscaria* is too low to play a role in the symptoms of poisoning.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The major toxins involved in *A. muscaria* poisoning are muscimol (3-hydroxy-5-aminomethyl-1-isoxazole, an unsaturated cyclic hydroxamic acid) and the related amino acid ibotenic acid.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Muscimol is the product of the decarboxylation (usually by drying) of ibotenic acid.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Muscimol and ibotenic acid were discovered in the mid-20th century.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Researchers in England, Japan and Switzerland showed that the effects produced were due mainly to ibotenic acid and muscimol, not muscarine.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] These toxins are not distributed uniformly in the mushroom.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Most are detected in the cap of the fruit, a moderate amount in the base, with the smallest amount in the stalk.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Quite rapidly, between 20 and 90 minutes after ingestion, a substantial fraction of ibotenic acid is excreted unmetabolised in the urine of the consumer.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Almost no muscimol is excreted when pure ibotenic acid is eaten, but muscimol is detectable in the urine after eating *A. muscaria*, which contains both ibotenic acid and muscimol.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Ibotenic acid and muscimol are structurally related to each other and to two major neurotransmitters of the central nervous system: glutamic acid and GABA respectively.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Ibotenic acid and muscimol act like these neurotransmitters, muscimol being a potent GABAA receptor agonist, while ibotenic acid is an agonist of NMDA glutamate receptors and certain metabotropic glutamate receptors which are involved in the control of neuronal activity.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] It is these interactions which are thought to cause the psychoactive effects found in intoxication.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Muscazone is another compound that has more recently been isolated from European specimens of the fly agaric.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] It is a product of the breakdown of ibotenic acid by ultraviolet radiation.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Muscazone is of minor pharmacological activity compared with the other agents.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] *Amanita muscaria* and related species are known as effective bioaccumulators of vanadium; some species concentrate vanadium to levels of up to 400 times those typically found in plants.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Vanadium is present in fruit-bodies as an organometallic compound called amavadine.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The biological importance of the accumulation process is unknown.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Fly agarics are best known for the unpredictability of their effects.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Seizures and coma may also occur in severe poisonings.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Symptoms typically appear after around 30 to 90 minutes and peak within three hours, but certain effects can last for several days.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] In the majority of cases recovery is complete within 12 to 24 hours.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The effect is highly variable between individuals, with similar doses potentially causing quite different reactions.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Some people suffering intoxication have exhibited headaches up to ten hours afterwards.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Retrograde amnesia and somnolence can result following recovery.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Medical attention should be sought in cases of suspected poisoning.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] If the delay between ingestion and treatment is less than four hours, activated charcoal is given.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Gastric lavage can be considered if the patient presents within one hour of ingestion.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Inducing vomiting with syrup of ipecac is no longer recommended in any poisoning situation.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] There is no antidote, and supportive care is the mainstay of further treatment for intoxication.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] If a patient is delirious or agitated, this can usually be treated by reassurance and, if necessary, physical restraints.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] A benzodiazepine such as diazepam or lorazepam can be used to control combativeness, agitation, muscular overactivity, and seizures.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Only small doses should be used, as they may worsen the respiratory depressant effects of muscimol.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Recurrent vomiting is rare, but if present may lead to fluid and electrolyte imbalances; intravenous rehydration or electrolyte replacement may be required.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Serious cases may develop loss of consciousness or coma, and may need intubation and artificial ventilation.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Hemodialysis can remove the toxins, although this intervention is generally considered unnecessary.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] With modern medical treatment the prognosis is typically good following supportive treatment.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The wide range of psychoactive effects have been variously described as depressant, sedative-hypnotic, psychedelic, dissociative, or deliriant; paradoxical effects such as stimulation may occur however.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Perceptual phenomena such as synesthesia, macropsia, and micropsia may occur; the latter two effects may occur either simultaneously or alternatingly, as part of Alice in Wonderland syndrome, collectively known as dysmetropsia, along with related distortions pelopsia and teleopsia.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Some users report lucid dreaming under the influence of its hypnotic effects.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Unlike *Psilocybe cubensis*, *A. muscaria* cannot be commercially cultivated, due to its mycorrhizal relationship with the roots of pine trees.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] However, following the outlawing of psilocybin mushrooms in the United Kingdom in 2006, the sale of the still legal *A. muscaria* began increasing.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Gordon Wasson that in remote areas of Lithuania, *A. muscaria* has been consumed at wedding feasts, in which mushrooms were mixed with vodka.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] She also reported that the Lithuanians used to export *A. muscaria* to the Sami in the Far North for use in shamanic rituals.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The Lithuanian festivities are the only report that Wasson received of ingestion of fly agaric for religious use in Eastern Europe.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] In eastern Siberia, the shaman would take the mushrooms, and others would drink his urine.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] This urine, still containing psychoactive elements, may be more potent than the *A. muscaria* mushrooms with fewer negative effects such as sweating and twitching, suggesting that the initial user may act as a screening filter for other components in the mushroom.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The Koryak of eastern Siberia have a story about the fly agaric (*wapaq*) which enabled Big Raven to carry a whale to its home.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] In the story, the deity *Vahiyinin* ("Existence") spat onto earth, and his spittle became the *wapaq*, and his saliva becomes the warts.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] After experiencing the power of the *wapaq*, Raven was so exhilarated that he told it to grow forever on earth so his children, the people, could learn from it.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Among the Koryaks, one report said that the poor would consume the urine of the wealthy, who could afford to buy the mushrooms.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] As a result of a lack of regulation, the use of *A. muscaria* as a popular legal alternative to hallucinogens has grown significantly in recent years.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] In 2024, Google searches for *Amanita muscaria* rose nearly 200% from the previous year, a trend that an article published in the *American Journal of Preventive Medicine* correlated with the sudden commercialisation of *A. muscaria* products on the internet.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] In 2025, the Federal Institute for Risk Assessment (BfR) of Germany stated that muscimol-containing products resembling sweets have appeared on the market and that they can cause serious intoxication, with children being particularly at risk.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] While Amanita mushrooms are unscheduled in the U.S., they are listed as a poison by the Food and Drug Administration (FDA).
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Amanita mushrooms and muscimol are not approved as an ingredient in food, with some drawing comparisons to the controversial legal status of hemp-derived cannabinoids.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The FDA is currently evaluating the use of *A. muscaria* and its constituents in dietary supplements, reminding manufacturers to ensure their ingredients meet safety standards and encouraging them to consult the Office of Dietary Supplement Programs with any questions.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] A recent outbreak of poisonings and at least one death associated with products containing *A. muscaria* extracts has sparked debates regarding the regulatory status of Amanita mushrooms and their psychoactive constituents, prompting an FDA ban of their use in food products in December 2024.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] These products often use misleading advertising, e.g. making erroneous comparisons to psilocybin mushrooms or not disclosing the inclusion of Amanitas on the packaging.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Itkonen mentions that *A. muscaria* was once used among the Sámi peoples.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Sorcerers in Inari would consume fly agarics with seven spots.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] In 1979, Said Gholam Mochtar and Hartmut Geerken published an article in which they claimed to have discovered a tradition of medicinal and recreational use of this mushroom among a Parachi-speaking group in Afghanistan.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] There are also unconfirmed reports of religious use of *A. muscaria* among two Subarctic Native American tribes.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Ojibwe ethnobotanist Keewaydinoquay Peschel reported its use among her people, where it was known as *miskwedo* (an abbreviation of the name *oshtimisk wajashkwedo* (= "red-top mushroom").
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] This information was enthusiastically received by Wasson, although evidence from other sources was lacking.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] There is also one account of a Euro-American who claims to have been initiated into traditional Tlicho use of *A. muscaria*.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The flying reindeer of Santa Claus, who is called Joulupukki in Finland, could symbolise the use of *A. muscaria* by Sámi shamans.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] However, Sámi scholars and the Sámi peoples themselves refute any connection between Santa Claus and Sámi history or culture.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The notion that Vikings used *A. muscaria* to produce their berserker rages was first suggested by the Swedish professor Samuel Ödmann in 1784. Ödmann based his theories on reports about the use of fly agaric among Siberian shamans.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The notion has become widespread since the 19th century, but no contemporary sources mention this use or anything similar in their description of berserkers.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Muscimol is generally a mild relaxant, but it can create a range of different reactions within a group of people.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] It is possible that it could make a person angry, or cause them to be "very jolly or sad, jump about, dance, sing or give way to great fright".
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Comparative analysis of symptoms have, however, since shown *Hyoscyamus niger* to be a better fit to the state that characterises the berserker rage.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Gordon Wasson proposed that *A. muscaria* was the *soma* talked about in the Rigveda of India, a claim which received widespread publicity and popular support at the time.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] He noted that descriptions of *soma* omitted any description of roots, stems or seeds, which suggested a mushroom, and used the adjective *hári* "dazzling" or "flaming" which the author interprets as meaning red.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] One line described men urinating *soma*; this recalled the practice of recycling urine in Siberia.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Soma is mentioned as coming "from the mountains", which Wasson interpreted as the mushroom having been brought in with the Aryan migrants from the north.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Indian scholars Santosh Kumar Dash and Sachinanda Padhy pointed out that both eating of mushrooms and drinking of urine were prescribed, using as a source the *Manusmṛti*.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] In 1971, Vedic scholar John Brough from Cambridge University rejected Wasson's theory and noted that the language was too vague to determine a description of Soma.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] In his 1976 survey, *Hallucinogens and Culture*, anthropologist Peter T.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Furst evaluated the evidence for and against the identification of the fly agaric mushroom as the Vedic Soma, concluding cautiously in its favour.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Kevin Feeney and Trent Austin compared the references in the Vedas with the filtering mechanisms in the preparation of *A. muscaria* and published findings supporting the proposal that fly-agaric mushrooms could be a likely candidate for the sacrament.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] There is established scholarly consensus that the botanical identity of soma/haoma is Ephedra (particularly Ephedra gerardiana, Ephedra intermedia, or *Ephedra equisetina*).
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The book was widely criticised by academics and theologians, including Sir Godfrey Driver, emeritus Professor of Semitic Philology at Oxford University and Henry Chadwick, the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] He concludes that if the theory were true, the use of the mushroom must have been "the best kept secret in the world" as it was so well concealed for two thousand years.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The toxins in *A. muscaria* are water-soluble: parboiling *A. muscaria* fruit bodies can detoxify them and render them edible, although consumption of the mushroom as a food has never been widespread.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The consumption of detoxified *A. muscaria* has been practiced in some parts of Europe (notably by Russian settlers in Siberia) since at least the 19th century, and likely earlier.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The German physician and naturalist Georg Heinrich von Langsdorff wrote the earliest published account on how to detoxify this mushroom in 1823.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] In the late 19th century, the French physician Félix Archimède Pouchet was a populariser and advocate of *A. muscaria* consumption, comparing it to manioc, an important food source in tropical South America that must also be detoxified before consumption.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Use of this mushroom as a food source also seems to have existed in North America.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] A classic description of this use of *A. muscaria* by an African-American mushroom seller in Washington, D.C., in the late 19th century is described by American botanist Frederick Vernon Coville.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] In this case, the mushroom, after parboiling, and soaking in vinegar, is made into a mushroom sauce for steak.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] It is also consumed as a food in parts of Japan.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The most well-known current use as an edible mushroom is in Nagano Prefecture, Japan.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] There, it is primarily salted and pickled.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] A 2008 paper by food historian William Rubel and mycologist David Arora gives a history of consumption of *A. muscaria* as a food and describes detoxification methods.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] They advocate that *A. muscaria* be described in field guides as an edible mushroom, though accompanied by a description on how to detoxify it.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The authors state that the widespread descriptions in field guides of this mushroom as poisonous is a reflection of cultural bias, as several other popular edible species, notably morels, are also toxic unless properly cooked.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The red-and-white spotted toadstool is a common image in many aspects of popular culture.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Garden ornaments and children's picture books depicting gnomes and fairies, such as the Smurfs, often show fly agarics used as seats, or homes.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Fly agarics have been featured in paintings since the Renaissance, albeit in a subtle manner.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] For instance, in Hieronymus Bosch's painting, *The Garden of Earthly Delights*, the mushroom can be seen on the left-hand panel of the work.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] In the Victorian era they became more visible, becoming the main topic of some fairy paintings.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Two of the most famous uses of the mushroom are in the *Mario* franchise (specifically two of the Super Mushroom power-up items and the platforms in several stages which are based on a fly agaric), and the dancing mushroom sequence in the 1940 Disney film *Fantasia*.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] An account of the journeys of Philip von Strahlenberg to Siberia and his descriptions of the use of the *mukhomor* there was published in English in 1736.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The drinking of urine of those who had consumed the mushroom was commented on by Anglo-Irish writer Oliver Goldsmith in his widely read 1762 novel, *Citizen of the World*.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] The mushroom had been identified as the fly agaric by this time.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Other authors recorded the distortions of the size of perceived objects while intoxicated by the fungus, including naturalist Mordecai Cubitt Cooke in his books *The Seven Sisters of Sleep* and *A Plain and Easy Account of British Fungi*.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] This observation is thought to have formed the basis of the effects of eating the mushroom in the 1865 popular story *Alice's Adventures in Wonderland*.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] A hallucinogenic "scarlet toadstool" from Lappland is featured as a plot element in Charles Kingsley's 1866 novel *Hereward the Wake* based on the medieval figure of the same name.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Thomas Pynchon's 1973 novel *Gravity's Rainbow* describes the fungus as a "relative of the poisonous Destroying angel" and presents a detailed description of a character preparing a cookie bake mixture from harvested *A. muscaria*.
[src:amorphea/amanita-muscaria] Fly agaric shamanism—in the context of a surviving Dionysian cult in the Peak District—is also explored in the 2003 novel *Thursbitch* by Alan Garner.
[src:amorphea/amoeba-proteus] This protozoan uses extensions called pseudopodia to move and to eat smaller unicellular organisms.
[src:amorphea/amoeba-proteus] Food is enveloped inside the cell's cytoplasm in a food vacuole, where ingested matter is slowly broken down by enzymes.
[src:amorphea/amoeba-proteus] *A. proteus* inhabits freshwater environments and feeds on protozoans, algae, rotifers, and even other smaller amoebae.
[src:amorphea/amoeba-proteus] They are colorless, but they may have colored inclusions derived from their food.
[src:amorphea/amoeba-proteus] The first description of this amoeba is probably that of August Johann Rösel von Rosenhof who, in 1755, published drawings of an amoeboid protozoan he called the "little Proteus".
[src:amorphea/amoeba-proteus] Subsequently, various authors assigned Rösel's organism and other amoeboid protozoa various names: Carl Linnaeus termed Rösel's organism *Chaos protheus* in 1758.
[src:amorphea/amoeba-proteus] Otto Friedrich Müller referred to it as *Proteus diffluens* in 1786.
[src:amorphea/amoeba-proteus] In 1878, Joseph Leidy proposed the current name *Amoeba proteus* to describe Rösel's *Proteus*, *Proteus diffluens*, and another described amoeba *Amoeba princeps*.
[src:amorphea/amoeba-proteus] The Arp2/3 complex plays a crucial role in regulating actin polymerization and organization, localizing in the cortical actin network, discrete adhesion foci, and the perinuclear region.
[src:amorphea/amoeba-proteus] However, actin polymerization at the leading edge of migrating pseudopodia occurs independently of the Arp2/3 complex.
[src:amorphea/amoeba-proteus] Furthermore, the Rac/PAK pathway is involved in regulating cell migration, with the PAK kinase MIHCK acting as an effector for the Rac-like protein, and inhibition of MIHCK disrupts normal migration and pseudopod formation, although it does not directly affect actin polymerization.
[src:amorphea/amoeba-proteus] Although *Amoeba proteus* has most of the key proteins associated with sexual processes (as do other amoebae), no evidence of meiosis or sexual activity has been reported.
[src:amorphea/amorphea] The International Society of Protistologists, the recognised body for taxonomy of protozoa, recommended in 2012 that the term Unikont be changed to Amorphea because the name "Unikont" is based on a hypothesized synapomorphy that the ISOP authors and other scientists later rejected.
[src:amorphea/amorphea] It includes amoebozoa, opisthokonts, and apusomonads.
[src:amorphea/amorphea] Thomas Cavalier-Smith proposed a new phylum: Sulcozoa, which consists of the subphyla Apusozoa (Apusomonadida and Breviatea), and Varisulca, which includes the taxa Diphyllatea, Discocelida, Mantamonadida, Planomonadida and Rigifilida.
[src:amorphea/amorphea] Further work by Cavalier-Smith showed that Sulcozoa is paraphyletic.
[src:amorphea/amorphea] Apusozoa also appears to be paraphyletic.
[src:amorphea/amorphea] Varisulca has been redefined to include planomonads, *Mantamonas* and *Collodictyon*.
[src:amorphea/amorphea] A new taxon has been created - Glissodiscea - for the planomonads and *Mantamonas*.
[src:amorphea/amorphea] Again, the validity of this revised taxonomy awaits confirmation.
[src:amorphea/amorphea] Amoebozoa seems to be monophyletic with two major branches: Conosa and Lobosa.
[src:amorphea/amorphea] Conosa is divided into the aerobic infraphylum Semiconosia (Mycetozoa and Variosea) and secondarily anaerobic Archamoebae.
[src:amorphea/amorphea] Lobosa consists entirely of non-flagellated lobose amoebae and has been divided into two classes: Discosea, which have flattened cells, and Tubulinea, which has predominantly tube-shaped pseudopodia.
[src:amorphea/amorphea] The group includes eukaryotic cells that, for the most part, have a single emergent flagellum, or are amoebae with no flagella.
[src:amorphea/amorphea] The unikonts include opisthokonts (animals, fungi, and related forms) and Amoebozoa.
[src:amorphea/amorphea] By contrast, other well-known eukaryotic groups, which more often have two emergent flagella (although there are many exceptions), are often referred to as bikonts.
[src:amorphea/amorphea] Bikonts include Archaeplastida (plants and relatives) and SAR supergroup, the Cryptista, Haptista, Telonemia and Picozoa.
[src:amorphea/amorphea] One view of the great kingdoms and their stem groups.
[src:amorphea/amorphea] The Metamonada are hard to place, being sister possibly to Discoba or to Malawimonadida or being a paraphyletic group external to all other eukaryotes.
[src:amorphea/amorphea] Eukaryotes are thought to have emerged within the archaeal phylum Promethearchaeota.
[src:amorphea/amorphea] The unikonts have a triple-gene fusion that is lacking in the bikonts.
[src:amorphea/amorphea] The three genes that are fused together in the unikonts, but not bacteria or bikonts, encode enzymes for synthesis of the pyrimidine nucleotides: carbamoyl phosphate synthase, dihydroorotase and aspartate carbamoyltransferase.
[src:amorphea/amorphea] This must have involved a double fusion, a rare pair of events, supporting the shared ancestry of Opisthokonta and Amoebozoa.
[src:amorphea/amorphea] Cavalier-Smith originally proposed that unikonts ancestrally had a single flagellum and single basal body.
[src:amorphea/amorphea] This is unlikely, however, as flagellated opisthokonts, as well as some flagellated Amoebozoa, including *Breviata*, actually have two basal bodies, as in typical 'bikonts' (even though only one is flagellated in most unikonts).
[src:amorphea/amorphea] This paired arrangement can also be seen in the organization of centrioles in typical animal cells.
[src:amorphea/amorphea] In spite of the name of the group, the common ancestor of all 'unikonts' was probably a cell with two basal bodies.
